description: From Old French, from Late Latin practicus (“active”), from Ancient Greek πρακτικός (praktikós, “of or pertaining to action, concerned with action or business, active, practical”), from πράσσω (prássō, “I do”).

adjectives.description: practic (comparative more practic, superlative most practic)

examples: They that intend the practic cure of melancholy, saith Duretus in his notes to Hollerius, set down nine peculiar scopes or ends […].

entries.meaning: A person concerned with action or practice, as opposed to one concerned with theory.
